So if a group G is finite or free, then G has a presentation of this special form. If
Gx and G2 have such presentations, then the free product Gx * G2 does so as well.
We will show that no other groups have such presentations, and by doing so we will
prove
Theorem 2.2. A group G can be presented by a presentation of the form (2; T),
where T is a finite, monadic, Church-Rosser Thue system such that every element of 2
has an inverse of length one with respect to T iff G is a free product of a finitely
generated free group and finitely many finite groups.
We will use a result of Haring-Smith [13] that is based on the work of Stallings
[23], and that gives a geometrical (language) characterization of groups which are
free products of free groups with finite groups. This characterization is based on the
Cayley diagram of a presentation of the group by generators and defining relations.
Suppose that 2 = 2 + U 2_, where 2_= {a\a g 2 + }, 2 + n 2_= 0, and let
